This specific scenario—Parent p = new Child();—is the "Heart of Java." At Microsoft, they use this to see if you can distinguish between Type (the blueprint) and Instance (the reality).
Here is the detailed breakdown for your notes and interview prep.
1. Compile-Time (The "Security Guard" Phase)
Which one does the Compiler look at? The Reference Class (Parent).
The Logic: The compiler’s job is to ensure Safety. It doesn't know what will happen when the program actually runs; it only knows what you've promised.
The Check: When the compiler sees p.start(), it looks at the type of p. Since p is of type Parent, the compiler checks: "Does the Parent class have a method named start()?"
The Result:
If Parent has start(), the code compiles successfully.
If Parent does NOT have start(), the code fails to compile—even if the Child class has that method.
The Microsoft Analogy:
The reference Parent p is the Remote Control. If your remote doesn't have a "Start" button, you can't press it, regardless of how fancy the TV is.
2. Runtime (The "Action" Phase)
Which one does the JVM execute? The Actual Object Class (Child).
The Logic: Once the program is running, the JVM looks at the Actual Object sitting in the Heap memory.
The Mechanism (Dynamic Method Dispatch): The JVM follows the memory address stored in p to find the object. It sees that the object is actually an instance of Child.
The Execution: It checks if the Child class has overridden the start() method. If it has, the JVM executes the Child version. This is the essence of Runtime Polymorphism.
3. What happens in Memory? (Step-by-Step)
Imagine the code: Parent p = new Child();
Metaspace (Method Area): Java loads the class definitions for both Parent and Child. It creates a V-Table (Virtual Method Table) for both.
Parent V-Table: start() -> address of Parent's code.
Child V-Table: start() -> address of Child's code.
The Heap: A Child object is created. Inside this object, there is a hidden Class Pointer that points to the Child class definition in the Metaspace.
The Stack: A variable p is created. It stores the Memory Address of the Child object in the Heap.
The Call (p.start()):
The JVM looks at the address in p.
It jumps to the object in the Heap.
It follows the Class Pointer to find the Child class definition.
It looks up the V-Table of Child, finds start(), and executes the code at that specific address.
4. Summary for your Notes
Phase	Who is in charge?	Looks at...	Purpose
Compile-Time	Compiler (javac)	Reference Type (Parent)	To verify the method exists and is accessible.
Runtime	JVM	Object Type (Child)	To execute the most specific (overridden) version.
