You have just discovered one of the most famous "trick" questions in Java technical interviews!
Your observation is 100% correct: The Parent's method runs. But why?
This happens because you used the static keyword. In a Microsoft interview, this is the distinction between Method Overriding and Method Hiding.
1. The Rule: Static Binding (Method Hiding)
When a method is static, it does not use the "Dynamic Method Dispatch" (the TV analogy) we discussed. Instead, it uses Static Binding.
Instance Methods (Non-static): The JVM looks at the Object in the Heap at Runtime. (Overriding).
Static Methods: The JVM looks at the Reference Type at Compile-time. (Hiding).
In your code:
Parent5 p1
←
←
 The Reference Type is Parent5.
p1.compute() is a call to a static method.
The compiler says: "Since the reference is Parent5, I will bond this call to Parent5.compute() right now."
It doesn't even bother looking at the Child5 object in the heap.
2. Method Overriding vs. Method Hiding
Feature	Method Overriding (Instance)	Method Hiding (Static)
Keyword	No static	Uses static
Binding	Dynamic (Runtime)	Static (Compile-time)
Decided by	The Object (new Child5())	The Reference (Parent5 p1)
Result in your code	Would print "hii child"	Prints "hii parent"
3. The "Interview Catch"
If I were your Microsoft interviewer, I would ask you this follow-up:
Interviewer: "If I remove the word static from both Parent5.compute() and Child5.compute(), what will the output be?"
The Answer: It would print "hii child".
Why? Because without static, it becomes a normal instance method. The JVM will use Dynamic Method Dispatch, look at the actual Child5 object in the heap, see the overridden method, and run it.
4. Why does Java do this? (Deep Logic for Notes)
static means "belonging to the class."
Because static members belong to the class blueprint and not the individual house (object), Java designers decided they should be linked as early as possible (at compile-time) to make the program faster.
